## Migration: `TimedExecutor` → .NET 8

### What Breaks

| API | .NET 8 Status |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** |
| `ThreadAbortException` | Never thrown; type exists but is vestigial |

`Thread.Abort()` was removed because it corrupts application state — it can fire mid-`finally`, mid-lock, or mid-write, leaving objects half-initialized.

### Modern Replacement: Cooperative Cancellation + `Task.Run`

```csharp
using System;
using System.Threading;
using System.Threading.Tasks;

public class TimedExecutor
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Executes <paramref name="work"/> with a timeout using cooperative cancellation.
    /// The work delegate must observe the <see cref="CancellationToken"/> to stop promptly.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        Task<T> task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Block the caller, just like the original thread.Join(timeout) did.
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        // Any other exception propagates unwrapped (no AggregateException)
        // thanks to GetAwaiter().GetResult().
    }

    // Overload for async callers (preferred in modern code)
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Callers Must Change Too

**Before (.NET Framework):**
```csharp
var executor = new TimedExecutor();
var data = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    () => SlowDatabaseCall(),        // no cancellation awareness
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

**After (.NET 8):**
```csharp
var executor = new TimedExecutor();
var data = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    ct => SlowDatabaseCall(ct),      // pass token through
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### If You Can't Change the Work Delegate

When wrapping uncooperative code that ignores `CancellationToken`, you can **abandon** the task without aborting the thread:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeoutUncooperative<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    Task<T> task = Task.Run(work);

    if (task.Wait(timeout))
        return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();

    // Task keeps running on a threadpool thread — it is orphaned, not killed.
    // This is the same risk as the old Thread.Abort(), but without corruption.
    throw new TimeoutException(
        $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
}
```

> ⚠️ **Use this only as a stopgap.** The orphaned thread keeps consuming CPU/memory. Prefer fixing the downstream code to accept `CancellationToken`.

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Orphaned work** | Unlike `Thread.Abort()`, cancellation is *cooperative*. If work ignores the token, it keeps running silently in the background. |
| **`Task.Result` wraps exceptions** | `task.Result` wraps in `AggregateException`. Use `GetAwaiter().GetResult()` to get the original exception. |
| **`Task.Wait(timeout)` ≠ cancellation** | Returning `false` from `Wait` means *you* stopped waiting, not that the work stopped. Always pair with `CancellationToken`. |
| **`Thread.ResetAbort()` in catch blocks** | Delete these entirely. If you leave `catch (ThreadAbortException)`, it compiles but never triggers — dead code that misleads readers. |
| **`ConfigureAwait(false)`** | In library code, add `.ConfigureAwait(false)` to the `await` to avoid deadlocks in UI/ASP.NET callers. |
| **Dispose the CTS** | `CancellationTokenSource` is `IDisposable`. Always `using` it or you leak kernel timer handles. |
